//! Platform-agnostic ports + wire types for the vault sync client (v0.7.0 D7). The core depends on
//! NOTHING but these three injected ports — no `obsidian` import, no Node-only API, no regex
//! lookbehind (unsupported on iOS) — so the identical core runs in the v0.7.0 headless reference
//! client, the v0.7.1 desktop plugin, AND Obsidian mobile (Locked #6 / R4).
//! A line-level 3-way merge MODEL (v0.7.0 D8). The authoritative merge is server-side (Rust dmp,
//! `packages/core/src/sync/merge.rs`); this TS twin is the faithful server-model used by the
//! convergence/DST harness AND the unit-tested merge ladder. Its contract matches the Rust engine's
//! INTENT: a side that didn't change yields to the other; non-overlapping edits merge clean;
//! overlapping edits (or structural insert/delete the simple model can't align) conflict — the
//! safe direction (keep-both), never silent loss.
//! Scan-diff change detection (v0.7.0 D7 — the key mobile refinement, Locked #6): GENERATE the op
//! batch by reconciling the CURRENT vault listing against the persisted path→state map, rather than
//! trusting lossy filesystem events. `vault.on(...)` events are only dirty hints that schedule a
//! reconcile; a dropped event is recovered here because the next scan still sees the divergence.
//!
//! v0.7.1 D5 adds **explicit rename/move identity**: an optional `RenameHint[]` (supplied by the
//! plugin from `vault.on('rename')`) lets a path change preserve the stable server node id — emitted
//! as `move`/`rename` ops — instead of degrading to trash(old)+create(new) (which would mint a new id
//! and break node-scoped share links). The hints are processed FIRST, re-keying `byPath` so the
//! scan-diff below sees the node already at its new path.
//! Small path helpers shared across the sync core (keep-both conflict allocation). Pure string
//! logic — no platform dependency.
//! Apply a pull delta to the local vault + persisted state (v0.7.0 D7). Trashed rows are applied as
//! local deletes; live rows land their `(id, rev, body)` as the new merge base.
//! v0.7.1 — **never clobber in-flight local edits** (the apply-merge, the fix for the "typing gets
//! truncated mid-sync" bug). A cycle is push-then-pull, but the user keeps typing DURING the
//! round-trip, so the body on disk when the pull lands can be NEWER than the snapshot the push sent.
//! The pull re-delivers our own just-pushed node (an echo), and a blind write would revert those
//! extra keystrokes. So instead of overwriting, we 3-way merge the live local body onto the incoming
//! server body, using **the body we pushed THIS cycle (`pushedBodies`) as the merge base** — that is
//! exactly what the server already knows about our edits:
//!   - no concurrent typing (`cur === pushed`) ⇒ `merge(P, P, server)` → `Clean(server)` → identical
//!     to the old blind write (so the DST/convergence harness and server-authoritative keep-both are
//!     unchanged);
//!   - typed more (`cur = P + extra`), no concurrent server change ⇒ `merge(P, cur, P)` →
//!     `Clean(cur)` → the keystrokes survive;
//!   - typed AND an overlapping concurrent server edit ⇒ conflict ⇒ keep-both (the local body moves
//!     to a fresh sibling), never silent loss.
//! The recorded base stays the SERVER body (`n.body`), so any preserved local delta re-pushes next
//! cycle and the server folds it in — convergence is unchanged.
//! Content-hash rename recovery (v0.7.4 D5). Identity preservation degrades to a `RenameHint` —
//! an in-memory signal the plugin derives from `vault.on('rename')`. When that hint is LOST (the app
//! restarts mid-conflict-copy, a rename event is dropped, or a cross-scope move-out is later widened
//! back in), a plain scan-diff sees only `trash(old)` + `create(new)` and the node id (with its
//! share links, backlinks, url_history, revisions) is reborn. This module recovers the lost identity
//! from the file BODY: a tracked file that disappeared WITHOUT a tombstone, paired one-to-one by
//! EXACT body with a brand-new untracked file, is almost certainly that same note moved/renamed. We
//! emit a synthesized rename hint so the existing rename machinery preserves the id.
//! Safety rails (every sync tool — Syncthing/Unison/git — uses the same heuristic):
//!  - EXACT body equality only (no fuzzy/hash-collision window; the bodies are in memory).
//!  - UNIQUE on both sides — if two notes share a body, neither side is unique ⇒ no pairing ⇒ the
//!    always-safe trash+create stands. The body must be non-trivial (empty/whitespace notes are far
//!    too common to pair).
//!  - TOMBSTONED disappearances are honored as deletes, NOT renames — an intentional in-app delete is
//!    never silently turned into a move (mirrors the v0.7.3 confirmed-vs-suspect-absence rule).
//!  - An EXPLICIT hint always wins — content recovery only fills the gap where no hint survived.
//! The vault sync orchestrator (v0.7.0 D7). Wraps the three injected ports and drives the protocol:
//! PUSH local changes first (so an unpushed local edit is never clobbered by an incoming pull),
//! then PULL authoritative state. Handles exactly-once `lastMutationID`, the cursor keyset, the
//! resync epoch (409 → full resync), the over-stale `resyncRequired` signal, and `413` batch
//! splitting. Pure + deterministic given its ports — the headless reference client and the v0.7.1
//! plugin both inject platform adapters around this identical core.
//! In-memory reference adapters (v0.7.0 D7). A `MemoryVault` + `MemoryStatePort` — the platform
//! pieces the headless reference client and the test harness inject around the platform-agnostic
//! core. (The v0.7.1 plugin swaps these for Obsidian's `Vault`/`DataAdapter` + an IndexedDB state
//! port; the core is unchanged.) Pure web-standard JS — no Node-only API.
//! `@docli/sync-client` — the platform-agnostic Obsidian vault-sync core (v0.7.0 D7). Inject the
//! three ports (`VaultPort`, `HttpTransport`, `StatePort`) and drive [`SyncClient`]. Reused verbatim
//! by the v0.7.0 headless reference client and the v0.7.1 Obsidian plugin (desktop + mobile).
